{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17641907","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17641907"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T19:34:26+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T19:34:26+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17917"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17917","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17917"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.74,0.06,0.12,0.03,0.06]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10631"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72817"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10631","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10631"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17917"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58287"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"81"},{"type":"tags","id":"1227"},{"type":"tags","id":"2207"},{"type":"tags","id":"2932"},{"type":"tags","id":"4534"},{"type":"tags","id":"4929"},{"type":"tags","id":"4940"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"10015"},{"type":"tags","id":"10770"},{"type":"tags","id":"11244"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24767"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24771"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72817","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/72817"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 55-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a six-month history of increased thirst and frequent urination. She has a medical history of obesity and hypertension. Her medications include lisinopril and metformin. She does not smoke or consume alcohol. On examination, she appears well with a pulse rate of 78/min, blood pressure 130/85 mmHg, and BMI of 32 kg/m\u003Csup\u003E2\u003C/sup\u003E. Laboratory investigations reveal a fasting blood glucose level of 9.5 mmol/L (3.9-5.5) and HbA1c of 8.2% (4.0-5.6).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following mechanisms is most likely contributing to decreased B-cell function and mass in this patient?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Glucotoxicity","Lipotoxicity","Autoimmune destruction","Viral infection","Genetic mutation"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with symptoms and laboratory findings consistent with type 2 diabetes mellitus. In type 2 diabetes, chronic hyperglycaemia can lead to \u003Cstrong\u003Eglucotoxicity\u003C/strong\u003E, which impairs pancreatic B-cell function and mass. Glucotoxicity results from prolonged exposure to high glucose levels, leading to oxidative stress and apoptosis of B-cells.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELipotoxicity\u003C/strong\u003E is another mechanism that can impair B-cell function, particularly in the context of obesity, due to elevated free fatty acids. However, glucotoxicity is more directly related to the hyperglycaemic state described in this patient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAutoimmune destruction\u003C/strong\u003E is characteristic of type 1 diabetes, where the immune system attacks B-cells, leading to their destruction. This is less likely in this patient, who has type 2 diabetes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EViral infection\u003C/strong\u003E can lead to B-cell dysfunction in some cases, but there is no evidence of a recent viral illness in this patient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGenetic mutation\u003C/strong\u003E can predispose individuals to diabetes, but it is not the primary mechanism of decreased B-cell function and mass in this scenario.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Chronic hyperglycaemia can lead to glucotoxicity, which impairs B-cell function and mass.","Lipotoxicity, due to elevated free fatty acids, can also contribute to B-cell dysfunction and apoptosis.","Inflammatory cytokines can induce B-cell stress and apoptosis, reducing their function and mass."],"references":["Bender, D. A., \u0026 Cunningham, S. M. (2021). Introduction to nutrition and metabolism. CRC Press","Salway, J. G. (2016). Metabolism at a Glance. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Banday MZ, Sameer AS, Nissar S. Pathophysiology of diabetes: An overview. Avicenna J Med. 2020 Oct 13;10(4):174-188. doi: 10.4103/ajm.ajm_53_20. PMID: 33437689; PMCID: PMC7791288","Galicia-Garcia U, Benito-Vicente A, Jebari S, Larrea-Sebal A, Siddiqi H, Uribe KB, Ostolaza H, Mart\u00edn C. Pathophysiology of Type 2 Diabetes Mellitus. Int J Mol Sci. 2020 Aug 30;21(17):6275. doi: 10.3390/ijms21176275. PMID: 32872570; PMCID: PMC7503727","Banday MZ, Sameer AS, Nissar S. Pathophysiology of diabetes: An overview. Avicenna J Med. 2020 Oct 13;10(4):174-188. doi: 10.4103/ajm.ajm_53_20. PMID: 33437689; PMCID: PMC7791288"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58287"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17917"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58287","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/58287"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-22T08:45:16+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-22T08:46:54+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10631"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72817"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"posi